segments.text: Okay, my name is Colson Tuff, and you'd ask me how I got connected with the company and how I got to Houston.
Right.

I was with the University of California at Irvine when the University of Houston was on the threshold of a large enrollment gain because they went from a private institution to be public in the early 60s.
And they just started, and they were having problems with the billing program, so they
trying to find someone to head up that program, found me, and made me a good offer.
And I moved and came there.
Had you had a Houston connection?
No, no, no.
I hardly knew where Houston was.
Is that right?
But they knew you were doing the same thing there.
Yeah, I had been with the University of California for 12 years and had gone through a lot of the same kind of thing.
And of course, at that time, the University of California
you know, still underway in a huge program, and I've been involved in that right from the beginning.
So I went to the University of Houston and...
So you got there in Houston about... 68.
Mm-hmm.
And we had a lot of work going on on the main campus, and it was a single-campus institution at that time.
And then around 69, the coordinating board had done some studies of population growth in Texas and areas and then recommended
at the University of Houston established two branch campuses, one to the north and one to the south of the city of Houston.
And I had the responsibility of trying to locate where these campuses would be.
We also had to get the land free, and we had to have it serviced by Rosie Utilities at no cost to the state, which was quite an undertaking to try to get it.
So anyway, we had a small graduate center down in the Clear Lake area, near Clear Lake City, near NASA, had 50 acres.
And so I began negotiations with the Friendswood Company towards acquiring the land.
That was successful.
I think we received around 340 acres or something like that, and then began the planning for the Clear Lake campus as it exists now.
That's a nice campus.
It is.
It turned out real nice.
Alfred Newman was the chancellor.
And Alfred was dean of arts and sciences at the main campus at that time.
And I knew him there.
And I had the concept of trying to create a gallery of education, of having it all in one building.
Because coming from California and seeing those kids walking from class to class through the heat and the rain, that was quite a different experience for me.
And so I thought, try to have all the academic facilities in one large galleria-type building, rather than having all these little separate buildings.
And so that's how we did the first phase of development.
Well, at about the same time, we had to find land to the north.
I had heard about Kingwood beginning to start, which was the development of Friendswood and the King Ranch.
And then someone told me about George Mitchell planning to start a new development, which was not at that time called the Woodlands, but it was going to be a new development north of the city.
So I had made appointments with the people at Kingwood for Dr. Hoffman, who was president of the University of Houston at the time, and myself to go meet with them.
And we toured that area.
And then we made an appointment to meet with Mr. Mitchell.
to tour what was going to be the woodlands.
At that time, Interstate 45 was here.
You could just come over the bridge, and it just stopped at this end, this forest from there.
So we had that meeting.
We had a tour with Mr. Mitchell, and that must have been about around maybe 1970.
At that point, did Mitchell describe
if you remember anything about what his plans were.
Oh, yes.
We had the meeting up here.
And then we were impressed with what we saw.
And we invited Mr. Mitchell to come and make a presentation to the Board of Regents.
And he did.
And he came with a member of his staff.
And Mr. Mitchell made an excellent presentation, very impressive, on what his plans were.
He already had some master plan drawings that had been prepared by some architects, which pretty well
It has not been a great change from that until here.
There's a lot of changes, but the general broad concept was there.
And he made a very impressive presentation.
What was impressive about it?
Well, just the scope of it, the type of planning.
He had hired Ian McHarg, who was really well-known, what you might call environmental planner now.
He was into doing the kind of planning that people talk about today.

20 years ago, he was doing that planning, how you would plan the land, study the soils, the vegetation, the natural drainage areas, the geology of the land, and then use that as a base for then doing your land planning.
Were you intrigued then with the fact that it didn't seem to be a typical kind of development?
That's right.
That it wasn't typical, and also it was on a large scale.
and was going to be a quality development.
He had also hired William L. Praer, who was an architect, who I knew from California.
Because William L. Praer, when I was at the University of California, each of the campuses had a consulting architect.
And we had one for, at that time, we were starting Santa Cruz, San Diego, and Irvine.
And I had William L. Praer as my consulting architect.
Isn't that right?
See, I was the university architect.
So I knew Pereira real well, and he was doing the master planning, the land plan based on all the environmental planning that Ian McHarg was doing.
And then they had other financial consultants and people who were in kind of market analysis and so forth.
But it's just the way Mr. Mitchell described it was very impressive.
Plus, as I say, the scale of it.
So then I think the next thing that's happened is that a small group of the regents, I remember the chairman came out, and I think Mrs. Wortham even came out.
The chairman, I think, was Colonel Bates at the time.
And anyway, a small group of us came out to have a tour of the woodlands.
And after that, we had a meeting, and I had recommended
that we negotiate with the Mitchell Company to acquire the land for the North Campus.
So it was my job then to work with the people who were what is now called the Woodlands Corporation.
This is a small group of people who were involved in doing the planning at that time.
So I was representing the University of Houston, negotiating with them to acquire the land.
And I had determined that we should get 400 acres of land.
And so I had a number of meetings with Mr. Mitchell's planning staff at that time.
And then I had occasion to meet with him a couple of times.
And I was impressed with him and the plans that were underway.
And that was satisfactorily concluded.
We reached an agreement on the land.
We had options to get it subject to approval by the coordinating board and the state.
And then that probably concluded that maybe around
71 or something like that.
And then of course we had to do a lot of paperwork.

And I don't know, for one reason or the other, 73 I made the decision because of my opportunities to meet Mr. Mitchell and being impressed with him and what he was planning, I thought it would be wonderful to come here because I'd seen all that kind of planning and development take place at the Irvine Ranch when I was at Irvine.
And I liked the scale of that size of operation.
Now, you're an architect.
You were .
Right, right, right.
So I liked that type of operation.
So anyway, I made the decision to leave the University of Houston in 1973 and come with the Mitchell Energy and Development Corporation.
And we then had our offices in One Shell Plaza, downtown Houston.
And in 1974,
April of 74, we moved into this building.
And this was the only building that was here in the Woodlands at that time.
The access was Woodlands Parkway here, and that was about the end of the roads.
What was your job when you first came on?
Pretty much what it is now.
At that time, I was involved more in the overall general planning.
And when we moved here, as we started the building program,
I moved into building development.
And my title now is senior vice president for design and construction.
In the beginning, I was heading up all building development that included residential also.
We weren't doing much in the way of residential development ourselves as a company, because what we did was plan the land, put in the roads, utilities, and plat it.
And then we would sell the lots to the individual
Home builders.
To the home builders.
You didn't hold those lots and then when the building was built, jointly sell?
No, we would just sell it to the builders.
A builder would buy 10 lots or 50 lots.
He would then build out those, sell those.
But we did build some townhouses called Settler's Corner Townhouses, which was our first residential development.
And I was involved in the
second phase of the build out of those.
The first phase was the first occupants on the woodlands in the first phase of that Settler's Corner development.

And when I got here, I took over finishing up the second phase of that and then finishing up some of the work at the wharf and the Indian Country Club, things that had still not been finished when we moved out here.
And then pretty much got into building development.
We then did planning for some apartments.
And of course, at that time, we were also doing some office buildings.
We did four of these buildings, this one right here.
There's one right over there, and one across the other corner, and one over here.
So we did four of these buildings.
That came a couple of years after we had built this one.
What's your role in terms of the design?
Well, let me amplify that question a little bit.
Historically, I noticed the Woodlands has a homogenous architectural style to it.
Not just the buildings here, but the residential areas as well.
Where did that come from?
How did that develop?
And I guess the other thing I'd like to know is a little bit more precisely, or nuts and bolts, how you integrate
or work, you know, your efforts at design and planning and with everything else that's going on around here?
Okay.
There's a few ways that it works.
We have in our division, commercial industrial division of the Williams Corporate.
You probably know there's residential, commercial, industrial.
And then there's what they call Mitchell Southwest.
Those are the major divisions of the Williams Corporation.
And then we have staff departments of planning, engineering, legal, and so forth.
In our division, we have what we call a regular land development meeting and a regular building development meeting.
And what we do at those meetings is bring in all the plans or proposals for land sales
for review by the people that attend that meeting.
It'd be just like a campus planning committee.
It's almost the same thing as we had a campus planning committee.
All proposals come in.

They'd be reviewed at that committee for conformance with our general plan, conformance with our marketing program, and then to determine the availability of the site in terms of utilities or roads or what have you.
So that's how the land plans would come in.
Building plans come in the same way.
As we determine that we're going to do, let's say we're going to do an office building, we'll select an architect to design that building.
We develop a budget for it.
We do a pro forma for it.
Know what I mean by pro forma?
It's the economic model for that particular building project.
And then as we...
get the concept design, we review that at our building development meeting.
Again, just like the campus planning committee meeting.

And we then get the input from everyone who's involved in that, and that would include maybe the sales and leasing people, the property management people, our construction people, our planning people, in terms of what do they think about that, how does that conform with our design guidelines, what we're trying to accomplish.
And of course,
You know, it can vary a little bit with the site, but generally because of the participants involved, there's some continuity there.
We also have what we call a development standards committee within the woodlands, which is a part of the organization or the creation of the woodlands.
The development standards committee is set up as an overall design review board.

all plans for development within the woodlands, which includes not only our company's plans, but for any developer who buys land for us, any home builder, all those plans have to go through for approval, for design and conformance with the development standards that have been created and adopted by the woodlands.
So there's a lot of review.
Is that part of the deed restriction, basically?
It's part of the deed restriction.
It's part of the woodlands charter.
Who developed the standards?
We did.
The Woodlands Corporation prepared the standards.
We employed consultants.
This goes back probably 17, 18.
Is that before you came?
No, I was involved in the initial commercial industrial standards.
We employed consultants to give us advice on the standards, not only for here, but then in the Woodlands Trade Center, which is an 800-acre parcel north of here.
And we employed consultants who were expert in doing that kind of work to give us recommendations, which we would then review and decide what we'd want to adopt.
Did the commercial industrial sector develop early on, or was that sort of a spin-off later?
All the building development, I said it was in one area at one time.
And then at that time, our organization of the company was along, what I'd say, functional lines.
There was just, you know, like planning and building design, and then there was sales and leasing.
Do you think you made your residential at that time?
No, no.
The sales and leasing, in other words, the vice president for, let's say, marketing, sales and leasing, also handled residential, commercial, industrial, everything.
We were all kind of straight line down like that.
When I think it was Ed Lee became president of the company,
he reorganized it from like a functional department into operating divisions.
And then each operating division had the responsibility for their planning, design, construction, marketing, sales, leasing, all within that division.

So residential was created as a separate division, commercial industrial as another, and then all the other properties, which includes, you know, Cape Royal and Pirates Beach and Galveston and all that was all put under
what is called Mitchell Southwest Properties.
So each of those divisions then had a head.
And then within each division are people who are responsible for carrying out the marketing goals for that division.
So I fit in the commercial industrial division responsible for building design and construction.
When the commercial industrial division was developed independently, was there already a pretty good
format or policy or program in mind as to where you're going and what you're going to try to do in terms of development?
Yes, in a general way.
But in commercial industrial, of course, residential is the same way.
You're very dependent on the market.
I mean, you can make all the plans you want.
But if nobody wants to buy it, it doesn't mean anything.
And so we started off with this area right where we're at being our initial commercial development, because we had this street in, we had that street in, and we had the beginning of this street here.
So in order to minimize your costs, you tend to want to put your buildings in the area where you had all your money in roads and utilities, because you want to put a building here.
It may cost you $2 million to get from here to there.
to build a building that may have cost $3 million.
So you just don't do it.
So what you try to do is we try to cluster there.

But then as the road would get extended to here and then maybe a piece of the road go here, then we develop maybe a cluster of parcels around that point and would say, OK, our marketing strategy is to sell these parcels to small office users.
like maybe medical building or small lot users for development.
And then we would create an area over here that would be available for large purchasers, like Pennzoil, who bought 40 acres from us, for example.
So we did have a marketing plan, but we could have a situation where somebody would come in and say, well, I want 15 acres, and I want it here, and I want this, and this, and this.
If we want to try to make a sale, we've got to be responsive to them within reason as to what we could afford to do.
I'm talking now on third-party sales.

Now, where we are building the building ourself, it would be because we want to build the buildings for our own account because we saw the opportunity to build that building and lease that space, and it makes it then an investment opportunity for us.
Plus, it enhances the overall.
Plus, it also sort of seeds the market.
Because if you had something going and get some people there, it then makes it more attractive for us.
That's right.
Well, also, we built this building to house all our real estate offices.
We moved here, as I said, in 74.
And we needed this building as a place to operate from.
And then as we had this, we built this building over there, and then these two over there.
And once we had this, then we leased the other buildings to other users.
Plus it gave us some expansion for other departments and divisions of the company.
After this nucleus of commercial buildings developed, which were all basically woodland coal and energy, what was the first big drill, you might say, right through our sale to a commercial?
Well, let's see.
I think the largest commercial land sale was Pennzoil for 40 acres.
And I can't remember when that was, but I'm going to guess that was maybe 10 years ago.
Had there been much before Pennzoil?
Oh, we've had other land sales in the Woodlands Trade Center, Eckerd Drug Distribution Center was a good one.
I don't know how many acres that is, maybe 20 acres or something like that.
That was a good sale.
Yeah, that's been there a long time, too.
Yeah, that was the first company to come into the Woodlands Trade Center.
And that probably was probably, I'm going to guess, in maybe a 77, 78 time period, something like that.
I kind of forget some of those years.
Those were probably two of the larger land sales.
We've had a number of other sales for smaller buildings throughout the woodlands.
How would you departmentalize, or maybe you shouldn't even, the commercial development projects?
In other words, I guess the mall is coming on, and you have the medical area.
I don't know if you could think of that as a distinct program,
complex, what other complex ?
Well, we have, as far as the major areas of development, we have where the regional mall will be located, Interstate 45.
Are you directly involved in that?
I'm directly involved in it.
However, we have a partnership agreement with the HOMART company.
HOMART is the development arm of Sears.
They're headquartered in Chicago.
We are putting in the land in the deal.
And Home Art will be the developers of that mall.
They will also lease and operate the mall.
We have a joint design approval on the design of the buildings.
And we, of course, are donating the land.
So we've been very much involved in the planning of the land, not only for the mall, but all the land around the mall.
For example, we're doing a study right now.
This is more current.
I get back to your question as far as major areas, but this is an area that we're planning right now, for example.
This is the southern part of the mall.
Interstate 45 is right here.
This is Timberlock.
And we're in an office probably down here somewhere.
So this is just an idea of a study plan for this particular area.
And we want to...
We want to begin the design on two or three major buildings in this area because we have the long range plans to develop the small.
We want to develop this lake here, which will act as a reservoir for flood control, but also can become an amenity.
So in order to locate where the initial buildings would go, we had to do this planning study.
for the alignment of these roads and the development of these parcels to determine how we lay the whole thing out to then determine where the initial buildings should go.

So this is the kind of work I do, working with our sales and leasing people who say, you know, these are the kind of buildings we ought to have, this is about roughly this size, so we have something to start with.
And I would work with our planning people
on the land plan of this area important, then I'd be responsible for coordinating this planning to come to an agreement within our group as to where we would begin.
And then once we begin, we resolve this planning, then I'd be working directly with the architects who we'd select to design the buildings.
You always go outside to do this?
Yeah, we only have four people on our staff.
We're very busy.
with the work that we've got going.
To do the kind of work we'd have to have dozens of people.
You're a management group.
Yes, we're just four persons who manage everything that we have going on.
So we've got, I mean, there's those lists up there.
I mean, that's just the first page of about three or four pages of projects that are going.
So we employ, consult, we farm everything out.
Our job is to manage the contracts with all the consultants that we employ.

We hire soil engineers, structural engineers, surveyors, architects, structural engineers, mechanical engineers, electrical engineers, illumination engineers, interior designers, landscape architects.
So we're hiring all those people and managing this whole process from beginning to end and then coordinating in-house
to arrive at the final product, and then also controlling the budget and the schedule.
It's kind of complex.
It is.
It's very complex.
If you're just doing, say, one at a time, and if you could just concentrate on one, it would be kind of fun.
But our situation is we throw up a whole bunch of balls in the air, and we keep moving.
You've got to try to keep them up in the air.
And this is just really starting.
Right.
This is just starting.
There's nothing here.
This road is in to I-45, and then there's nothing here.
So this is just the beginning of a small phase of this development in what we're now calling the town center.
So this will be a fascinating development as this goes on.
But anyway, you were asking about the different areas.
The mall is one large area.
There'll be development that will take place around the periphery of that area.
Another major component is the Trade Center, which is a rail serve distribution center type of complex.
been there about 10 or 12 years, the nucleus or the?
Oh, it's been, well, I mean, the Trade Center as a land parcel has been there since we started.
But the first building development was at the Drug and Distribution Center.
And that, I'm thinking, was we moved here in 74.
That was like 77 or 78, somewhere around that, I'm guessing.
And that's really exploded, not exploded, but it has developed nicely.
Yeah, it's developed nicely.
You expect much more in that area?
Oh, yes.

But the commercial development, I would say, has not gone as rapid as we had estimated when we began, mostly because there have been so many variations in the economy and outside influences affecting what we do.
And there are just forces that you can't control in this business.
probably we started planning our Esplanade property, which is south of Greensboro Mall area.
We have 180 acres there along Interstate 45.
We had hired a planning firm from Dallas, and we had probably started maybe about 1979, 1980 on the master planning for that development.
Very intense planning.
And we probably got the planning done, all our approvals.
rented space in an office building down there that overlooks the site, built a big exhibition center there.
And by that time, it was about 1983 or 82.
And boy, we were just going terrific, just like this.
And we got to the top.
We looked terrific.
Then we looked down, and it went just like that.
And we had hired the sales director to open that place up, and he opened it up.
And we probably closed it six months later.
Is everything still there, pending now?
No, the lease is gone, and the furniture is spread all around this building.
I don't know where the models are anymore.
We had these huge models with lights and everything.
It was beautifully done, beautifully done.
It's just that, like a lot of other people, no one could foresee the economic decline that was going to take place in the Houston area when the oil

business went went down and had you know tremendous tremendous impact on the Houston area so I'm not telling you anything new and of course it did here and since we are so far out from the Houston area we may have been affected up here sooner than other areas because most people tend to you know cluster towards the downtown area but I don't know if there's any perceptible time difference between the two but
We noticed it, and we started cutting back.
We had bids on an office building, a 12-story office building that we were going to build at the end of Timberlock, down near where this site is.
We had the bids.
We had just already left the contract, and we stopped on that project.
So those were difficult times.
But now, the Woodlands seemed, in a way, to have weathered that, especially in terms of residential buildings.
Better than none in a lot of other areas.
Well, the rest, I would say that the wind has weathered it.
It was very difficult times.
We cut back severely in our staff.
And I probably had, I think, maybe 14 people working at one time.
None of us were.
Well, the two in 10 improvement were sick.
So we cut more than half of the people away.
Anyway, the commercial really got cut back.
And we didn't do very much.
I'm trying to think of what we did do for a couple of years there.
Just small, small work.
Residential dropped a way off.
And that period probably lasted maybe four or five years.
But then we noticed in residential maybe four years ago that our residential sales were picking up.
And then the next year was really good, and the next year was even better, and the next year was better than that.
It just kept up going like this.
Well, what was happening is that while there were less people buying homes, the people who were buying were going to the planned communities.
So the Woodlands was getting a much larger share of the market than what it was getting before.
And I would assume it was because the people who were buying

because of what they'd seen had happened to values of homes and properties and everything, were going to the planned communities because they just instinctively recognized that there's where the value was because homes in the planned communities held up better than in a typical suburban development.
So our home sales started to do good and have been very good.
I mean, last year was good.
The year before that was good.
And this year has been excellent.
Now, you should be getting a commercial spinoff somewhere along the way.
Well, that's right, because just as when we began, we had very little commercial, and we didn't have anything in the way of retail services, you know, shops, stores, markets, or what have you.
We developed the population.
That population then wanted to have a drugstore and a grocery store and so forth.
So then, in following your question,
One of our other major areas of development in commercial were the village shopping centers.
So we built a village shopping center in Grover's Mill Village, and we did another one several years later at Panther Creek Village Center.
And, in fact, we're in the midst of remodeling Panther Creek because that's been so successful.
We're going to enlarge the Randall supermarket and do some revisions to the center.
to continue the expansion of that.
And we have done some advanced planning on another site along Research Forest Drive.
And those really were not part of the original planning.
Yeah, they were.
The basis of the original general plan was to have a series of villages.
Yeah.
Like six villages.
And each village would have some geographical definition to it and would have a group of schools, churches, shopping centers that were related to the scale of that village.
So yes, we always had in the plan, planning would just have like a blob on the map that this is a site for a general, this is set for a village center.
So then when we were ready,
we'd say, okay, we'll take that piece of land, and then we then will develop that piece of land.

Then I would hire planners and architects and so forth to then plan that piece of land so that we can build that out for our market program to have a supermarket and a drugstore and dry cleaners and all the other things that go with having a village center.
So going back, so you had the trade center, you have the...
regional mall area, you have the office buildings, you have the village centers.
Now another large area of our planning development has been the Woodlands Inn and Country Club, which is now called the Woodlands Executive Conference Center and Country Club and Resort.
So we had to be nucleus of the executive center and the country club when we opened.

since that time we've done a lot of remodeling of the existing buildings to continue upgrading the quality of the facilities and we've made a major conversion of one building which we called the wharf which was like a small mall and we remodeled that completely to provide expansion for the woodlands in for conference meeting rooms the mall died right yeah the mall was designed
Like, here's the parking lot, and the mall was a long, narrow building this way, rather than taking a building and putting it this way, like a strip center where all the stores could have visibility.
It was this way, so you had to get out of your car, walk into that mall, and walk through it like this.
Well, that might work in an area where you've got, say, a million people.
You know, all the apartments are out here, and then that becomes convenient for them.
But when you're in a suburban area like this, that just wasn't...
the thing to do.
And that never was successful.
We had it almost all leased up.
We had an ice skating rink in there.
And it started out leased up, but it became apparent that it was premature.
Because we only had a few hundred people here.
And as you know, to support a hardware store or something like that, you may need a population of 7,000 just to support a hardware store.
We just didn't have the population, so it was premature to start that development.
So it was one of the big mistakes.
We've made some mistakes, and we've learned as we've gone along.
When did the concept of a medical center develop in terms of building?
Well, we had in our general plan the intent to have a hospital.
The idea of getting the hospital in was moved ahead when I think it was Humana.
I think they wanted to either develop inside or outside the woodlands.
And we had already had started a plan for a family health center within the woodlands in a small building up Borges Mill Road.
with the intent that we would then go from there to the hospital as the population grew and the need developed to support that.
They came in to, and then they had to file a, what is it called, a certificate of, they had to file for a certificate of need or something like that for the state.
Well, we then got in competition with them, went through all our studies to support what we wanted to do.
We submitted ours to the state.
We got our approval based on that.
We then created a board to own the hospital.
We then hired the architects and designed and supervised the construction of that hospital, turned that over to that board.
So that was the nuclear stand-alone?
Yes.
Then from there, there has been developed a private development, which is a three-story medical office building on Lakefront Circle Drive.
And then we built a small professional building that connects to the hospital.
And the intent is that that area would then be the center of other medical-type buildings around the hospital and the hospital design so it could incrementally expand.
And do you see a lot of expansion developing in that area?
Are you doing much with that right now?
Not too much.
We had a second professional building planned
And we have not gone ahead with it because I think that the leasing activity has been very slow, just as it has been in all kinds of commercial office spaces.
And so we have not gone ahead and done that building.
Is your prime focus right now the wall, basically?
I mean, you personally.
Personally, well, right now I'm involved in buildings here in the woodlands.
buildings in Galveston, and then I work on buildings that Mr. Mitchell personally owns in Galveston.
In what way do you work on them?
Well, he has bought a number of old buildings in Galveston in the Strand area, which are pretty dilapidated.
And he started this probably around 1975 or 76.
when this program of, there were tax benefits for him, and also this occurred about the same time that Galveston had created the Galveston Historical Foundation.
And a new man was brought in, his name was Peter Brink,
They had raised some money through a pool, through the local banks, to try to buy some of these old buildings before they were torn down because it was a great collection of 1800s buildings.
Well, the National Register, too, came in and surveyed them.
Yeah, then what they did, they worked with the Department of the Interior to get that area declared a historical district so people couldn't come in and turn them into a pizza parlor

from our company who has been primarily working on that because that's been more a planning function and then when we get into the development part of it then probably other people will get involved if there's any building development from our standpoint we'll probably get involved in it would you say the prime motive of the commercial development in the woodlands has been to provide jobs for people who move here to make money for for the woodlands corporation
all of the above, or how does that fit into the scheme of things?

Well, it fits in the scheme in that what we're trying to do to make the whole woodland successful is to make it truly a new community and not have it just be a bedroom community where you live and then you commute 20 or 30 miles to some other place, work there, then come back here, sleep at night, and repeat that process.
So what we've been trying to do is create a job base here.
And so it serves a number of purposes.
One, by creating a job base here, that means that people can buy a home here, find a job here.
It gets away from this business of people commuting all over the place.
So we're really trying to create a new town or a satellite community, just like in new towns in Sweden and Finland and England and France.
although their approach is different.
They just say, you know, this is going to be it, and you will go there, and that's where you're going to be.

We're subject to the market forces of our economy, and we can't control anything except try to do a better job and give a better product at a better price to hope that people will then come in and move here.
So that's one part of it.
Another part of it is to make money, to make a profit to pay for this, because if we don't make a profit, we go broke, and nothing happens.
So...
One, we're trying to keep a job base.
By creating a job base, that makes it attractive for people to move in.
When people are moving in, that makes it attractive for retail people, the hardware store guy and the drug store guy, to move in because these people are here.
So you get a synergy going of these things affecting each other.
And then, of course, as I say, we hope to, because of the tremendous investment we're putting in the land development here,
realize some of the value that we're creating and build a building, hopefully, so we can then lease it and make some money off of it.

Well, it's very difficult because we're influenced by the whole
Houston metropolitan economy.

Generally, we've found that there becomes a hurting instinct, like West Houston has developed tremendously, the West Memorial, Houston area, Park 10, and all that.
I believe that's happened because all the managers, executives that were working downtown Houston all lived in that memorial area.
When this area west developed, they could still stay in their homes there.
The children could go to the same school.
Their wives could go shopping the same places.

Just change their focus a little bit.
That's right.
We've been at a point where we didn't have any trees here.
So we had to try to attract people to buy into here and then hope that those people could spin off some business or get here.

But we've had to really work it the other way and try to get the companies to build buildings here or to leave space for us in the buildings that we built in the hope of attracting them there and hoping that they would grow and then they would buy houses in the woodlands.
